FILE: /standards/SMPTE_ST_2084_PQ.sci

WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified standard reference for SMPTE ST 2084, the Perceptual
Quantizer (PQ) Electro‑Optical Transfer Function (EOTF). It defines
the exact equation that maps digital code values to absolute luminance
for HDR displays, covering the range 0 to 10 000 cd/m².

WHY IT EXISTS
PQ is the foundational HDR transfer function used in Dolby Vision,
HDR10, and GIOP HDR outputs. A single, verified definition of the
EOTF and its inverse is essential for any HDR pipeline.

HOW IT WORKS
The formula is derived from the Barten contrast sensitivity model,
ensuring that each code‑value step is at most one just‑noticeable
difference (JND).

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- All GIOP ODTs targeting HDR displays
- HDR mastering and quality control.

WHO USES IT
L2 Engineers implementing ODTs; L3 Colorists verifying HDR grades.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Prevents implementation divergence of the PQ curve, guaranteeing that
the same code value produces exactly the same luminance on any
GIOP‑compliant display.

KEY FORMULAS

1. PQ EOTF
   V = ((c1 + c2 * L^m1) / (1 + c3 * L^m1))^m2
   L: linear luminance (0 to 1, where 1 = 10 000 cd/m²)
   Constants:
     m1 = 2610 / 16384 = 0.1593017578125
     m2 = 2523 / 4096 * 128 = 78.84375
     c1 = 3424 / 4096 = 0.8359375
     c2 = 2413 / 4096 * 32 = 18.8515625
     c3 = 2392 / 4096 * 32 = 18.6875

2. Inverse PQ (OETF)
   L = ( (V^(1/m2) – c1) / (c2 – c3 * V^(1/m2)) )^(1/m1)
   for V in (0,1).

